{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/autism-in-adults/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"1d801996-d965-5a13-8911-e1e73561bc33","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 53989d6a-a951-44e3-9002-aa0600c8abe9 --><h1>Autism in adults: Summary</h1><!-- end field 53989d6a-a951-44e3-9002-aa0600c8abe9 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 3a2b37d7-ff65-4b6e-be47-aa0600c8abe9 --><!-- begin field 55ba567f-428a-46ea-8a28-aa0600c8abe9 --><ul><li>Autism spectrum disorder (ASD) is a lifelong neurodevelopmental condition characterized by persistent difficulties in social interaction and communication, and the presence of stereotypic (rigid and repetitive) behaviours, resistance to change, or restricted interests.</li><li>ASD is strongly associated with a number of coexisting conditions that may significantly impact on the wellbeing of the person and their family and/or carers.<ul><li>Mental health or behavioural disorders associated with ASD include anxiety and depression, attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, and learning (intellectual) disability.</li><li>Other conditions associated with ASD include sensory problems, gastrointestinal disturbances (such as inflammatory bowel disease, coeliac disease, diarrhoea, and constipation), and epilepsy.</li></ul></li><li>The autism spectrum is very wide, ranging from people with limited self-help, independence, academic, or verbal skills through to those who are fully independent but have significant social difficulties.<ul><li>The features of ASD may range from mild to severe, and the presentation varies greatly in different people. </li><li>The severity and impact of ASD differs at different stages of life, in response to interventions, and with the presence of coexisting conditions.</li></ul></li><li>The precise cause of ASD is unknown. However, a number of different genetic and environmental factors are thought to play a role in development.</li><li>The estimated prevalence in adults is about 1.1%.</li><li>ASD is a life-long disorder, but the prognosis can be improved by early diagnosis and assessment.</li><li>The diagnosis of ASD is established by a specialist following referral. Ideally, this is carried out by an autism team if available (or if not, by a psychiatrist).</li><li>Primary care management of people with confirmed ASD generally includes:<ul><li>Routine review, where appropriate.</li><li>Ensuring that the person with ASD has access to appropriate psychosocial interventions for managing core symptoms of ASD and improving life skills.</li><li>Ensuring that those with ASD and an associated mental health condition are offered appropriate pharmacological treatment or referred to an appropriate specialist.</li><li>Initial management of behaviour that challenges.</li><li>Giving the person with ASD and their family, partners, and/or carers verbal and written information on ASD and its management and information on local support groups and services.</li><li>Offering families, partners, and/or carers of adults with ASD an assessment of their own needs.</li></ul></li><li>Secondary care management includes:<ul><li>Specialist diagnostic and assessment services.</li><li>Specialist care and interventions.</li><li>Advice and training to other health and social care professionals on the diagnosis, assessment, care, and interventions for adults with ASD (as not all may be in the care of a specialist team).</li><li>Support in accessing, and maintaining contact with, housing, educational, and employment services.</li><li>Support to families, partners, and/or carers where appropriate.</li><li>Care and interventions for adults with ASD living in specialist residential accommodation.</li><li>Training, support, and consultation for staff who care for adults with ASD in residential and community settings.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 55ba567f-428a-46ea-8a28-aa0600c8abe9 --><!-- end item 3a2b37d7-ff65-4b6e-be47-aa0600c8abe9 -->","topic":{"id":"32496f22-23a5-5fd3-af9d-aaa3ee19e8c4","topicId":"7875afe5-1be7-4d7d-aaee-aa0600c8a8b5","topicName":"Autism in adults","slug":"autism-in-adults","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"1d801996-d965-5a13-8911-e1e73561bc33","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"9734a796-92be-5d8e-a449-165bb7c48303","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"923a675b-d678-557f-9c55-f812123295f0","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"c9e157b2-2b93-57bc-a59d-352858540bdf","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"44c0c065-104d-5b0e-910a-b79265e7660d","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"51bf61e4-2f0f-50af-9d9a-6e75814aa9db","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","subChapters":[{"id":"01492dc4-77e0-59c1-b4fd-5770732d8d51","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"641ca12c-43c4-5274-ba37-b332755227a3","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"421104c4-9e4d-5105-a6f2-b13e16769a87","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"24fbca3b-5d6b-5f86-aa0d-f57e4aebb9a0","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"ef3c19b0-d066-5a2c-8de9-9f9173a490d6","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"b6cc75c0-bb75-5789-992d-d9e97d9ae77f","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"a653ef4b-e179-59b1-a4d6-7e87ea470c57","slug":"background-information","fullItemName":"Background information","subChapters":[{"id":"ed2e7d98-0e83-561f-be20-a925d3de34b2","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition"},{"id":"da3472cb-1943-56b5-8882-6fcd83c3f90c","slug":"causes-risk-factors","fullItemName":"Causes and risk factors"},{"id":"f61a6e0e-dc1f-53b2-b699-99f4e31be15a","slug":"prevalence